1.2 dplyr verbs

dplyr is a package that transforms data.

filter() - extract cases
arrange() - reorder cases
select() - extract variables
mutate()- create new variables
summarise() - summarise variables / create cases

group_by() - group cases

Common syntax: each function take a data frame as its first argument and returns a data frame.

1.2.1 filter()

Extract rows that meet logical criteria.

filter(df, City == "Barcelona")
# A tibble: 7 x 4

1.2.5 summarise()

Compute table of summaries.

Take a vector as input. Return a single value as output.

summarise(df, n = n(), 
  Rev_total = sum(Revenue), 
  Rev_mean = mean(Revenue), 
  Tot_act = n_distinct(Activity))
# A tibble: 1 x 4
      n Rev_total Rev_mean Tot_act
  <int>     <int>    <dbl>   <int>
1   100    414449    4144.      55

1.3 %>% operator

The pipe operator %>% passes result on le into first argument of function on right.

df %>% 
    summarise(n = n(), 
      Rev_total = sum(Revenue), 
      Rev_mean = mean(Revenue), 
      Tot_act = n_distinct(Activity))
# A tibble: 1 x 4
      n Rev_total Rev_mean Tot_act
  <int>     <int>    <dbl>   <int>
1   100    414449    4144.      55

Shortcut to type %>%:

Cmd + Shift + M (Mac)

Ctrl + Shift + M (Windows)

1.3.1 group_by()

Groups cases by common values.

df %>% 
    group_by(City) %>% 
    summarise(n = n(), 
      Rev_total = sum(Revenue), 
      Rev_mean = mean(Revenue), 
      Tot_act = n_distinct(Activity))

Exercise:

  • How many companies are there in each city with a revenue> 3000 and how many with a revenue <3000?
df %>% 
    mutate(Volume = ifelse(Revenue > 3000, ">3000", "<3000")) %>% 
    group_by(City, Volume) %>% 
    summarise(n_3000 = n())
# A tibble: 26 x 3

2 Exercises

2.1 Exercise 1

  • Simulate a sample of size 10,000 of the following distributions: \(N (\mu = 5, \sigma = 3)\) and \(N(\mu = 7, \sigma = 1)\). Save the simulations in a tibble.
  • Calculate the product of the previous samples (you can use the mutate() function from the dplyr library).
  • Make a figure that compares its density functions (geom_density()). To do this, make a first graphic using facet and a second one overlaying the densities (you can use the parameter alpha to control the transparency of the densities).

2.2 Exercise 2

Use geom_function() to graphically represent:
- a Normal standard distribution,
- a \(\mathcal{N}(\mu = 7, \sigma=1)\) distribution and
- a \(Beta(a, b)\) distribution. Use several values of the \(a\) and \(b\) parameters and analyze how the density changes.
